	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Unfair competition is the main challenge for EU tropical tuna fleets </h1>

			
			<h4>
												20 January 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In early 2010 the EU Presidency decided to consult the European Economic and Social Committee (EESC) on the situation of the EU tropical tuna fleet and the challenges facing it. As a result, the EESC adopted an opinion highlighting that the main challenge for the sector is to survive in an environment of unfair competition with third-country fleets: ‘the high social, health, food safety, environmental, legal, maritime safety, governance and monitoring standards required by the Community system ... add to the cost of a product which has to compete with production from other countries which enjoy a looser approach to these aspects. The EU must continue to promote the application of all these elements in the world's other fleets, with the EU standard as the benchmark for other operators.’</p><p>The EU tuna fleet's principal competitors are the Asian purse-seining fleets operating in the Pacific Ocean, says the opinion: ‘These fleets mostly supply the largest tropical tuna-processing zone represented by the Thailand-Philippines-Indonesia triangle. Their products – of lower quality – are highly price-competitive on the European market, securing a 35% share despite facing a 24% tariff’.</p><p>The EESC also feels that maintaining the preferential systems without change, such as granting global sourcing to Papua New Guinea and Fiji, is of vital importance in ensuring the survival of the EU industry and its investment in third countries. With global sourcing, ‘the EU is encouraging over-exploitation of Pacific tuna resources ... Moreover, the companies that will gain zero-tariff access to the EU market are mainly Asian ones, who are being encouraged to boost canned production capacity on a market where prices have been pushed down by excess supply ... It may also provide a means of ‘laundering’ products from illegal fisheries.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
‘The situation of the EU tropical tuna fleet and the challenges facing it’, European Economic and Social Committee Opinion, NAT 459, 15 September 2010<br/>
<a href="http://eescopinions.eesc.europa.eu/EESCopinionDocument.aspx?identifier=ces%5Cnat%5Cnat459%5Cces1175-2010_ac.doc&amp;language=EN" target="_self">http://eescopinions.eesc.europa.eu/EESCopinionDocument.aspx?identifier=c...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Whilst there may little doubt that Asian tuna fleets have lower operating costs, the EESC analysis seems to have overlooked the high levels of public funding that benefit EU tropical tuna fleets active in high seas and ACP EEZs, which artificially lower their operating costs. Nevertheless it is important to note that an increasing number of EU institutions, like the European Parliament and the EESC, as well as some key EU member states, are now advocating that the EU promote the international application of the same social, health, food safety, environmental, legal, maritime safety, governance and monitoring standards that it applies to EU fleets. This will manifest itself not only through EU diplomatic action in international fora (WTO, FAO, RFMOs) but also through the application of more stringent standards on EU imports, including through trade relations with ACP countries, in order to create a ‘level playing field’ between EU fleets and their Asian competitors.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
